definition[0]: to attack or criticize someone suddenly or violently
example[0]: Unhappy young people will often strike out at the people closest to them.
definition[1]: to draw a line through something written on a piece of paper
definition[2]: to start walking or swimming in a particular direction, especially in a determined way
example[1]: She struck out for the side of the pool.
definition[3]: to start doing something or living independently
definition[4]: to not hit the ball in baseball three times, so that you are not allowed to continue trying, or to make someone do this
example[2]: He struck out the first batter he faced.
definition[5]: to not be successful at something
example[3]: ‘Did she say she’d go out with you?’ ‘No, I struck out.’
definition[6]: to say officially that something cannot be considered as proof in a court of law
definition[7]: to start doing something new, without other people’s help
example[4]: He left the family business and struck out on his own.
